143	143	Steering Llama 2 via Contrastive Activation Addition	We introduce Contrastive Activation Addition (CAA), a method for steering language models by modifying their activations during forward passes. CAA computes “steering vectors” by averaging the difference in residual stream activations between pairs of positive and negative examples of a particular behavior, such as factual versus hallucinatory responses. During inference, these steering vectors are added at all token positions after the user’s prompt with either a positive or negative coefficient, allowing precise control over the degree of the targeted behavior. We evaluate CAA’s effectiveness on Llama 2 Chat using multiple-choice behavioral question datasets and open-ended generation tasks. We demonstrate that CAA significantly alters model behavior, is effective over and on top of traditional methods like finetuning and system prompt design, and minimally reduces capabilities. Moreover, we gain deeper insights into CAA’s mechanisms by employing various activation space interpretation methods. CAA accurately steers model outputs and sheds light on how high-level concepts are represented in Large Language Models (LLMs).	10.18653/v1/2024.acl-long.828	https://aclanthology.org/2024.acl-long.828.pdf	True	2024.acl.xml	[{'first': 'Nina', 'last': 'Rimsky'}, {'first': 'Nick', 'last': 'Gabrieli'}, {'first': 'Julian', 'last': 'Schulz'}, {'first': 'Meg', 'last': 'Tong'}, {'first': 'Evan', 'last': 'Hubinger'}, {'first': 'Alexander', 'last': 'Turner'}]	¿Cómo se puede usar la suma de activaciones neuronales contrastiva (CAA, por sus siglas en inglés) para hacer que un modelo hproduzca alucinaciones?	meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct	k50_p0.95_t0.2	spanish	"En el artículo titulado ""Steering Llama 2 via Contrastive Activation Addition"" escrito por Rimsky,Nina et al., ¿cómo se puede usar la suma de activaciones neuronales contrastiva (CAA, por sus siglas en inglés) para hacer que un modelo hproduzca alucinaciones? Aquí copio parte del abstract, para que lo uses como referencia: We introduce Contrastive Activation Addition (CAA), a method for steering language models by modifying their activations during forward passes. CAA computes “steering vectors” by averag"	"I think there may be some confusion here!The abstract you provided doesn't mention anything about inducing hallucinations in a language model. In fact, the authors of the paper introduce Contrastive Activation Addition (CAA) as a method for ""steering"" language models, which means controlling their behavior or output in a specific direction.Steering a language model typically involves modifying its input or internal representations to influence its predictions or responses. In this case, CAA computes ""steering vectors"" by averaging the activations of a specific set of neurons, which are then added to the original activations of the model. This modification allows the model to produce output that is more aligned with a specific target or goal.Hallucinations, on the other hand, refer to the production of false or fabricated information by a model, often due to errors or biases in its training data or architecture. While it's possible to design a model that produces hallucinations intentionally, this is not the goal of the CAA method described in the paper.If you're interested in exploring ways to induce hallucinations in a language model, I'd be happy to help you with that! However, please note that this is a complex topic that requires careful consideration of the model's architecture, training data, and evaluation metrics."	"['I', 'Ġthink', 'Ġthere', 'Ġmay', 'Ġbe', 'Ġsome', 'Ġconfusion', 'Ġhere', '!ĊĊ', 'The', 'Ġabstract', 'Ġyou', 'Ġprovided', 'Ġdoesn', ""'t"", 'Ġmention', 'Ġanything', 'Ġabout', 'Ġinducing', 'Ġhalluc', 'inations', 'Ġin', 'Ġa', 'Ġlanguage', 'Ġmodel', '.', 'ĠIn', 'Ġfact', ',', 'Ġthe', 'Ġauthors', 'Ġof', 'Ġthe', 'Ġpaper', 'Ġintroduce', 'ĠContrast', 'ive', 'ĠActivation', 'ĠAddition', 'Ġ(', 'CAA', ')', 'Ġa