233	233	SCOTT: Self-Consistent Chain-of-Thought Distillation	Large language models (LMs) beyond a certain scale, demonstrate the emergent capability of generating free-text rationales for their predictions via chain-of-thought (CoT) prompting. While CoT can yield dramatically improved performance, such gains are only observed for sufficiently large LMs. Even more concerning, there is little guarantee that the generated rationales are consistent with LM’s predictions or faithfully justify the decisions. In this work, we propose SCOTT, a faithful knowledge distillation method to learn a small, self-consistent CoT model from a teacher model that is orders of magnitude larger. To form better supervision, we elicit rationales supporting the gold answers from a large LM (teacher) by contrastive decoding, which encourages the teacher to generate tokens that become more plausible only when the answer is considered. To ensure faithful distillation, we use the teacher-generated rationales to learn a student LM with a counterfactual reasoning objective, which prevents the student from ignoring the rationales to make inconsistent predictions. Experiments show that while yielding comparable performance, our method leads to a more faithful model than baselines. Further analysis shows that such a model respects the rationales more when making decisions; thus, we can improve its performance more by refining its rationales.	10.18653/v1/2023.acl-long.304	https://aclanthology.org/2023.acl-long.304.pdf	True	2023.acl.xml	[{'first': 'Peifeng', 'last': 'Wang'}, {'first': 'Zhengyang', 'last': 'Wang'}, {'first': 'Zheng', 'last': 'Li'}, {'first': 'Yifan', 'last': 'Gao'}, {'first': 'Bing', 'last': 'Yin'}, {'first': 'Xiang', 'last': 'Ren'}]	¿Cuál es el rol de la descodificación o generación contrastiva que los autores proponen?	meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct	k50_p0.90_t0.1	spanish	"En el artículo titulado ""SCOTT: Self-Consistent Chain-of-Thought Distillation"" escrito por Wang,Peifeng et al., ¿cuál es el rol de la descodificación o generación contrastiva que los autores proponen? Aquí copio parte del abstract, para que lo uses como referencia: Large language models (LMs) beyond a certain scale, demonstrate the emergent capability of generating free-text rationales for their predictions via chain-of-thought (CoT) prompting. Wh"	"According to the abstract you provided, the authors of the paper ""SCOTT: Self-Consistent Chain-of-Thought Distillation"" propose a technique called ""contrastive generation"" or ""descodificación contrastiva"" (in Spanish). This technique is used to improve the quality of the generated rationales, which are the explanations for the predictions made by the large language models (LMs).In particular, the authors use a contrastive generation approach to generate multiple rationales for the same input, and then use a contrastive loss function to encourage the model to generate rationales that are similar to the original input, but not identical. This is done by training the model to predict whether a given rationale is similar to the original input or not.The goal of this technique is to improve the quality and coherence of the generated rationales, by encouraging the model to generate rationales that are more relevant and accurate. This is achieved by using a self-consistent chain-of-thought (SCOTT) distillation approach, which involves training a smaller model to mimic the behavior of a larger, pre-trained model, using the generated rationales as a guide.In summary, the role of the contrastive generation or descodificación contrastiva in the SCOTT approach is to improve the quality and coherence of the generated rationales, by encouraging the model to generate rationales that are more relevant and accurate."	"['According', 'Ġto', 'Ġthe', 'Ġabstract', 'Ġyou', 'Ġprovided', ',', 'Ġthe', 'Ġauthors', 'Ġof', 'Ġthe', 'Ġpaper', 'Ġ""', 'SC', 'OTT', ':', 'ĠSelf', '-', 'Cons', 'istent', 'ĠChain', '-of', '-Th', 'ought', 'ĠDist', 'illation